The paper discusses the development of a full-stack mmWave module for end-to-end simulation of 5G cellular systems, which involves various aspects of networking and communication, such as physical layer, medium access control, congestion control, and core network. Therefore, the most likely category is cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture). The paper also mentions statistical channel models, real measurements, and ray-tracing data, which are related to information theory and signal processing, suggesting cs.IT (Information Theory) as the second likely category. The use of advanced architectural features, such as dual-connectivity, may fall under cs.AR (Hardware Architecture), while the focus on mmWave technology and its potential for multi-gigabit and low latency wireless links may relate to cs.MM (Multimedia). Finally, the paper emphasizes the use of discrete-event network simulation and the integration with an open-source simulator, which may fall under cs.COMM (Computers and Society).
